comments.body: That's all very helpful info, @akiley. I will keep this all in mind the next time I see juvenile gulls in this area. Thanks for enlightening me!

Hi bobby23.  I will try to explain why this is a Herring over the other three main gulls that are possible.  

A juvenile Ring-billed (which seem to be much less common in the Northeast than Herrings of the same age) whoud be much smaller, compact, and petite in structure, with a smaller bill as well.  

A juvenile Lesser Black-backed (pretty uncommon, but does show up) would show a darker, almost more patterned back than contrasts with a lighter brown, streaked belly, and a whiter head.  

A Great Black-backed would be similar in plumage to a juv or first-winter Herring, but be noticibly larger than Herring, LBB or anything else (it is the largest gull  in the world), and a very thick bill.  Juvenile gulls are tough, but definitely possible with experience!
Hi, @sgalick. Thanks for the species-level suggestion. Could you please explain your assertion that it's a Herring Gull? I don't know what characteristics to look for to differentiate juveniles.
